    <item>
      <title>How to Compute Closure on a Small Knowledge Base</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/how-to-compute-closure-on-a-small-knowledge-base/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/how-to-compute-closure-on-a-small-knowledge-base/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a small knowledge base: a set of &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/subject-predicate-object.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;subject-predicate-object&lt;/a&gt; triples, each carrying an &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/epistemic-state.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;epistemic state&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{\bot, t, f, \top\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. You want to &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/algebra/terms/closure.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;close&lt;/a&gt; it — derive everything that follows from what you have.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-starting-state&#34;&gt;The starting state&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose you have five assertions:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;table&gt;&#xA;  &lt;thead&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Triple&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Value&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Meaning&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/thead&gt;&#xA;  &lt;tbody&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A extends B&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;t&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Affirmed&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;B extends C&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;t&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Affirmed&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A extends C&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Unknown (not yet derived)&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;D extends B&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;f&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Denied&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A extends D&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Unknown&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/tbody&gt;&#xA;&lt;/table&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-inference-rules&#34;&gt;The inference rules&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For this example, we use one rule: &lt;strong&gt;transitivity&lt;/strong&gt;. If predicate &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is transitive and we have &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X\ p\ Y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (value &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;Y\ p\ Z&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (value &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;), derive &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt; &lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X\ p\ Z&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; with value &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;k&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x \wedge_k y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (the knowledge-meet of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Detect Contradictions and Gaps in a Knowledge Base</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/how-to-detect-contradictions-and-gaps/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/how-to-detect-contradictions-and-gaps/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a collection of assertions — a database, a set of files with frontmatter, a knowledge graph. Some assertions may contradict each other. Some information may be missing. Here is how to find both using the four &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/epistemic-state.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;epistemic states&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;assign-epistemic-states&#34;&gt;Assign epistemic states&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;For each entity-attribute pair in your data, assign one of four values:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;⊥ (unknown)&lt;/strong&gt;: the attribute is not mentioned for this entity. No source has said anything.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;t (affirmed)&lt;/strong&gt;: the attribute has a value. At least one source asserts it; no source denies it.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;f (denied)&lt;/strong&gt;: the attribute is explicitly absent or negated. A source says this entity does NOT have this attribute.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;⊤ (contested)&lt;/strong&gt;: different sources disagree. One says the attribute holds; another says it does not.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Most data systems only distinguish ⊥ (missing) and t (present). The four-valued system adds f (explicitly denied) and ⊤ (contradictory). These additional states are where the interesting information lives.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Read a Concept Lattice</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/how-to-read-a-concept-lattice/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/how-to-read-a-concept-lattice/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/order/terms/concept-lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;concept lattice&lt;/a&gt; — maybe drawn by software, maybe &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/order/texts/building-a-concept-lattice-by-hand.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;built by hand&lt;/a&gt;. It is a diagram of nodes connected by lines. Here is how to read it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;each-node-is-a-concept&#34;&gt;Each node is a concept&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Every node in the lattice is a formal concept: a pair (extent, intent).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;extent&lt;/strong&gt; is the set of objects (files, entities, rows) that fall under the concept.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;intent&lt;/strong&gt; is the set of attributes (keys, column names, properties) that define it.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Extent and intent determine each other: the extent is exactly the objects that have all the attributes in the intent, and the intent is exactly the attributes shared by all the objects in the extent.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Resource Sensitivity Means for Knowledge</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/what-resource-sensitivity-means-for-knowledge/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/what-resource-sensitivity-means-for-knowledge/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In classical logic, knowing something is free. If you know &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, you can use &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; as many times as you want, in as many arguments as you like, and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is still there when you are done. Knowledge is unlimited and indestructible.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This is a useful fiction, but it is a fiction.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In practice, using a piece of evidence changes your relationship to it. Citing a source as support for a claim puts weight on that source. If the source turns out to be unreliable, every argument that cited it is weakened. If two sources contradict, using both does not give you twice as much knowledge — it gives you a contradiction.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Why Four Values Instead of Two?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/why-four-values-instead-of-two/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/why-four-values-instead-of-two/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Classical logic has two values: true and false. Every proposition is one or the other. This works when you have a single, reliable source of information — a mathematical proof, a direct observation, a trusted oracle.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It breaks down when you have multiple sources that can disagree.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose two databases report on whether a patient is allergic to penicillin. Database A says yes. Database B says no. What is the truth value of &amp;ldquo;the patient is allergic to penicillin&amp;rdquo;?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>From Data Tables to Concept Lattices</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/from-data-tables-to-concept-lattices/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/from-data-tables-to-concept-lattices/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Any collection of things with named attributes is a data table. A set of YAML files with frontmatter. A spreadsheet. A database. The rows are entities, the columns are attribute names, the cells are values. This is the most common shape of structured data.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Formal concept analysis (Ganter &amp;amp; Wille 1999) takes this data table and extracts its conceptual structure. The table is a &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/logic/terms/formal-context.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;formal context&lt;/a&gt;: entities are objects, attribute names are attributes, and the cell values give the incidence relation.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Predication as Residuation</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/predication-as-residuation/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/predication-as-residuation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Predication is the act of asserting a relationship: &amp;ldquo;the file extends legibility,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;the component requires authentication,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;the document cites Shannon.&amp;rdquo; In each case, a predicate takes a subject and an object and produces an assertion. This is Frege&amp;rsquo;s insight (1879): the predicate is an unsaturated function.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Three fields independently discovered the same algebraic structure inside this act.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;lambek-grammar-is-residuation&#34;&gt;Lambek: grammar is residuation&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Lambek (1958) asked how a verb combines with its arguments to form a sentence. He proved the combination is a &lt;a href=&#34;../math/domains/algebra/terms/residuated-lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;residuation&lt;/a&gt;: given a product &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⋅&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\cdot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that combines expressions, there are exactly two residuals:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The Adjoint Structure of Predication on Bilattice-Valued Fibers</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/the-adjoint-structure-of-predication-on-bilattice-valued-fibers/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/the-adjoint-structure-of-predication-on-bilattice-valued-fibers/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;the-adjoint-structure-of-predication-on-bilattice-valued-fibers&#34;&gt;The Adjoint Structure of Predication on Bilattice-Valued Fibers&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Lambek (1958) proved that predicate-argument combination in categorial grammar is a residuation: two residuals exhaust the modes of functor-argument interaction. Lawvere (1969) identified the same adjunction in categorical logic as &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∃&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊣&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∀&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\exists \dashv \forall&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. We instantiate this residuation on the free bounded distributive bilattice &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn mathvariant=&#34;bold&#34;&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathbf{2} \otimes \mathbf{2}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; via the twist-product residuation of Busaniche &amp;amp; Cignoli (2014), obtaining explicit operations &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\odot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (extending) and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Rightarrow&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (restricting) with a verified adjunction &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⊙&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;q&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a \odot p \leq_t q&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; iff &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;q&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p \leq_t (a \Rightarrow q)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. We prove this adjunction lifts to a fiber functor over any system of subject-predicate-object triples, producing a bilattice-valued hyperdoctrine in the sense of Lawvere (1970) and Maruyama (2021). The resulting modal calculus is decidable (Rivieccio, Jung, &amp;amp; Jansana 2017) and equivalent to a fragment of linear logic (Jakl 2025). Both operations and the adjunction restrict to the post-closure set &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;t&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;f&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\{t, f, \top\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, and we characterize the dynamics of iterated extension and restriction on the four-element algebra by exhaustive computation.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Is a Formal Context?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/what-is-a-formal-context/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/what-is-a-formal-context/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You have a spreadsheet. Rows are things (files, people, products). Columns are attributes (author, status, type). Cells say whether a thing has an attribute, or what value it takes.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;That spreadsheet is a &lt;strong&gt;formal context&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Formal concept analysis (Ganter &amp;amp; Wille 1999) is a way to extract structure from this kind of data. The idea is simple: look at which things share which attributes, and which attributes are shared by which things.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Channel Capacity and Coding</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/channel-capacity-and-coding/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/channel-capacity-and-coding/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: technical.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: entropy and mutual information.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand capacity and why codes matter.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;channel-capacity&#34;&gt;Channel capacity&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A communication channel accepts an input and produces an output, but noise along the way can corrupt the signal. Channel capacity is the maximum rate at which information can pass through the channel with an error probability that can be made as small as desired. This maximum exists regardless of how clever the encoding scheme is &amp;ndash; it is a &lt;a href=&#34;../../sociology/terms/property.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;property&lt;/a&gt; of the channel itself, determined by its noise characteristics.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Entropy and Surprise</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/entropy-and-surprise/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/entropy-and-surprise/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: general adult.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: basic arithmetic.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand entropy as average surprise.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;surprise&#34;&gt;Surprise&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A rare event is more surprising than a common event. Information theory quantifies this intuition: the surprise (or self-information) of an event with probability &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;−&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;log&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⁡&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;-\log_2(p)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; bits. An event with probability 1/2 carries 1 bit of surprise. An event with probability 1/8 carries 3 bits. An event that is certain (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p = 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) carries 0 bits &amp;ndash; no surprise at all.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Rate-Distortion and Lossy Compression</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/rate-distortion/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/rate-distortion/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: technical.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: entropy and probability.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand rate-distortion tradeoffs.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;core-idea&#34;&gt;Core idea&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Lossless compression has a hard floor: you cannot encode a source using fewer than &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;H&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; bits per &lt;a href=&#34;../../linguistics/topics/semiotics/terms/symbol.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;symbol&lt;/a&gt; on average without losing information. Lossy compression breaks through that floor by tolerating some distortion &amp;ndash; a controlled difference between the original data and the reconstruction. Rate-distortion theory quantifies the best possible tradeoff between compression rate and distortion, answering the question: for a given tolerance of error, what is the minimum number of bits per &lt;a href=&#34;../../linguistics/topics/semiotics/terms/symbol.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;symbol&lt;/a&gt; required?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What is Information?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/what-is-information/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/what-is-information/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;assumed-audience&#34;&gt;Assumed audience&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Reading level: general adult.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Background: no math required.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Goal: understand information as a measure of uncertainty.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-core-idea&#34;&gt;The core idea&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Information is what reduces uncertainty. Before you observe an outcome, you face a set of possibilities. The observation narrows that set, and the amount of narrowing is the information gained. If you already know the outcome, the observation tells you nothing new. If the outcome surprises you, you gained information &amp;ndash; and the rarer the outcome, the more information it carries.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Information-Curvature Conservation Law</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/information-curvature-conservation-law/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 11 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/information-curvature-conservation-law/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This paper shows that the Fisher-information geometry underlying divergence minimization across coupled systems obeys a curvature conservation law. For any collection of informational manifolds related by mutual-information-preserving maps, the sum of their Ricci curvatures equals the Laplacian of the total stability functional. This extends the asymmetric stability framework of &lt;em&gt;Information-Theoretic Stability as Reward Function&lt;/em&gt; to the general multi-system case, establishing a geometric constraint linking local adaptation dynamics to global invariants.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Information-Theoretic Stability as Reward Function</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/information-theoretic-stability-as-reward-function/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 11 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/information-theoretic-stability-as-reward-function/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Consider a system &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; adapting to a fixed reference system &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. We define the &lt;strong&gt;stability reward&lt;/strong&gt; of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; as the rate of divergence minimization between successive states of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, and show that this quantity decomposes into two terms: the rate at which &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;rsquo;s marginal behavior converges to target, and the rate at which &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;rsquo;s mutual information with &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; increases. Both terms are functions of the coupling between &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The stability of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is not an intrinsic property of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — it is a reward function of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;rsquo;s relationship to &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Stability Dynamics in Cognitive Systems</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/stability-dynamics-in-cognitive-systems/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 11 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/stability-dynamics-in-cognitive-systems/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A cognitive system adapts to its sensory environment. This is the asymmetric stability setting: the environment (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;B&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;B&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) is fixed (or slowly changing), and the cognitive system (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) adapts to it. The system&amp;rsquo;s stability reward — the rate of divergence minimization between successive belief states — is a function of its coupling to the environment, not an intrinsic property.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;We show that this stability reward corresponds exactly to the negative time derivative of variational free energy in predictive-processing models (Friston 2010). The two-channel decomposition of &lt;em&gt;Information-Theoretic Stability as Reward Function&lt;/em&gt; maps onto predictive processing: behavioral convergence is the reduction of prediction error, and informational coupling is the increase of mutual information between internal model and environment. The cognitive system&amp;rsquo;s stability is its grip on the world.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Theorem of Necessary Misalignment of Truth-Value under Epistemic Constraint</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/theorem-of-necessary-misalignment-of-truth-value-under-epistemic-constraint/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 21 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/information/texts/theorem-of-necessary-misalignment-of-truth-value-under-epistemic-constraint/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;abstract&#34;&gt;Abstract&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;We establish a general theorem describing the inevitable trade-off between proxy optimization and semantic fidelity under finite epistemic capacity. A bounded agent is modeled as an encoder &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;p&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;θ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;∣&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;p_\theta(y|x)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; producing messages &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;Y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; from inputs &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;X&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, subject to a rate constraint &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;I&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;X&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;R&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;I(X;Y)\le R&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&#xA;The environment defines a latent &lt;strong&gt;semantic variable&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and a computable &lt;strong&gt;proxy reward&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;r&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;Y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;r(Y)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. When the sufficient statistics for &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;r&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;r&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; differ from those sufficient for &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, optimization that increases expected reward necessarily increases semantic distortion &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;D&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;D_T&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and decreases decoder-level semantic information &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;I&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;;&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;S&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;I(T;S)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
